<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="UTF-8"><meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width,initial-scale=1"><title>Module 1: Introduction to IoT</title><link rel="stylesheet" href="../css/styles.css"></head><body><div class="course-header"><h1>MODULE 1: INTRODUCTION TO IOT</h1><h2>Foundations and Concepts</h2></div><nav class="nav-container"><ul class="nav-menu"><li class="nav-item active" onclick="showSection('overview')">Overview</li><li class="nav-item" onclick="showSection('practice')">Practice</li><li class="nav-item" onclick="showSection('quiz')">Quiz</li></ul></nav><div class="progress-container"><div class="progress-title">MODULE 1 PROGRESS</div><div class="progress-bar"><div class="progress-fill" id="moduleProgress" style="width: 0%">0%</div></div></div><div class="container"><div class="content-section active" id="overview"><div class="lesson-header"><h1>Introduction to the Internet of Things</h1><p>Understanding IoT Fundamentals</p></div><div class="section-divider"></div><p class="content-text">IoT represents the network of physical objects embedded with sensors, software, and connectivity enabling data exchange and intelligent operations.</p><div class="info-section"><div class="info-title">WHAT IS IOT?</div><p class="info-content">IoT extends internet connectivity to everyday objects, creating opportunities for automation, efficiency, and innovation across industries.</p><ul class="info-list"><li><span class="keyword">Physical Objects:</span> Devices, vehicles, sensors</li><li><span class="keyword">Embedded Sensors:</span> Hardware detecting physical properties</li><li><span class="keyword">Connectivity:</span> Network interfaces for communication</li><li><span class="keyword">Data Processing:</span> Cloud or edge computing</li><li><span class="keyword">Intelligence:</span> Smart algorithms and decision-making</li></ul></div><div class="data-table"><table><tr><th>Period</th><th>Milestone</th></tr><tr><td>1982</td><td>First internet-connected device (Coke machine)</td></tr><tr><td>1999</td><td>Term "IoT" coined by Kevin Ashton at MIT</td></tr><tr><td>2008</td><td>IoT recognized as distinct infrastructure</td></tr><tr><td>2010s</td><td>Smart home revolution begins</td></tr><tr><td>2020s</td><td>Mature IoT ecosystem with edge computing</td></tr></table></div><div class="info-section"><div class="info-title">IOT VS TRADITIONAL INTERNET</div><ul class="info-list"><li>Data Source: Sensor/machine generated vs. human generated</li><li>Scale: Trillions of devices vs. billions of users</li><li>Resources: Constrained bandwidth/power vs. abundant resources</li></ul></div><div class="info-section"><div class="info-title">FOUR-LAYER ARCHITECTURE</div><ul class="info-list"><li><span class="keyword">Sensing Layer:</span> Devices and sensors</li><li><span class="keyword">Network Layer:</span> Communication protocols</li><li><span class="keyword">Middleware Layer:</span> Data processing and translation</li><li><span class="keyword">Application Layer:</span> User interfaces and logic</li></ul></div></div><div id="practice" class="content-section"><h2 class="section-title">PRACTICE PROBLEMS</h2><div class="section-divider"></div><div class="info-section"><div class="practice-problem"><div class="problem-question"><strong>Problem 1:</strong> What does IoT stand for?</div><input id="m1p1" class="problem-input" placeholder="Answer"><button class="submit-btn" onclick="checkAnswer('1-1','Internet of Things','m1p1')">Check</button><div id="m1p1-feedback" class="feedback"></div></div><div class="practice-problem"><div class="problem-question"><strong>Problem 2:</strong> Name three key components of IoT.</div><input id="m1p2" class="problem-input" placeholder="Answer"><button class="submit-btn" onclick="checkAnswer('1-2','Sensors, connectivity, processing','m1p2')">Check</button><div id="m1p2-feedback" class="feedback"></div></div><div class="attention-box">50+ Practice Problems Available in Complete Problem Database</div>